ises the indigenous experience, and makes cross-cultural comparisons, especially with island communities. It employs the methods of sociocultural anthropology and includes the multidisciplinary findings of tourism studies: in doing so it is innovative and challenges standard understandings of the influence of specific types of tourism on small communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTourismxCanary IslandsxGomera. 0aTourismxSocial aspectsxCanary IslandsxGomera. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszCanary IslandszGomera. 0aTourismxSocial aspects. 0aTourismzCanary IslandszGomera. 0aTourism. 0aTourismexAspect socialxCanariesxGomera. 0aTourismexAspect social. 0aTourismexCanariesxGomera. 0aTourisme. 4aSustainability. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aLa Gomera.  acultural change.  aglobalisation.  ahosts and guests.  aidentity.  aisland community.  atourism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCVP eBook-Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311075437740uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978187315073340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781873150733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781873150733.jpg  a978-3-11-075437-7  CVP eBook-Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK